  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "HO",
    "text": "The picture is of my mother and her cousin and her brother and some other close family members, which was taken approximately 1924, four years before she was married. The picture was taken and she was born in the city by the name of [INAUDIBLE]. And that is a family outing long before I was born. This picture is of my uncle and myself. His name was Herbert Haas. It was taken in 1938 as the last picture I have of him and me before he went to the United States. The uncle and his wife are the ones that brought me to Los Angeles in 1946. But this is from 1938. This is a picture of my aunt, whose name was Bertha Haas. It was taken in 1938, again, when I was 10 years old, shortly before they left for the United States. And it was taken, like the picture of my uncle, in Cologne, Germany. These two pieces, these striped pieces, are each a piece of the uniform I wore when I was liberated in Buchenwald on April 11, 1945. The centerpiece with the name of it must apparently have come off some kind of supply, a bag of some sort, the content of which I don't know that the Germans had used to designate it that it was supposed to go to the concentration camp. I saved these sort of as a souvenir, as a remembrance of times past. In an apparent attempt to eliminate as many prisoners and kill off as many as they could shortly before the liberation in April of 1945, the Germans attempted with an enormous firepower to shoot into the barracks and various open places. And while we were laying down waiting for who knows what, this bullet grazed my temple and got lodged in the wood of the barrack. And I dug it out and I saved it as a souvenir. Oh this is a picture of me, Henry Oster, taken in 1945 in Paris. And the reason I have this picture is that it was the first hair that I had grown after the liberation from the concentration camp. For more than four years, our hair was very short. And in the concentration camp itself, it had to be shaven every month. So here, with a great deal of pride, I'm showing off my first hair.",
